 &gt;From:  Paul Mockapetris &lt;pvm@edu.isi.venera&gt;
 &gt;Subject: Re: leading digits in domain names
 &gt;Date:  Thu, 23 Apr 87 17:50:32 PDT

 &gt;Now if we are using a domain name for a host name or a mail domain, we
 &gt;have to combine the restrictions from the domain system and the
 &gt;application spec to get the set of usable names.  The problem with 3COM
 &gt;is an 822 issue not a 882 issue.

It is even narrower than this!   RFC 822 allows for any
(non-"special") character in a domain component, and certainly
does not prevent leading digits.  The only mail protocol I know
of with the leading digit restriction is SMTP (RFC 821).
Thus 3com.edu is fine in a mail message, as long as it is not
delivered by SMTP!   (I suspect, but have not checked, that
telnet and FTP also have the digit restriction).

Steve

PS For what it is worth, I agree with Marvin's analysis on why
the protocols in question should be changed.

